          <teaser><![CDATA[Ever wondered just how the different cars of F1 2010 stack up against each other for outright performance.  Look no further, we've done the hard work so you don't have to. ]]></teaser>
          <author>Rob Gray</author>
          <authorUrl><![CDATA[]]></authorUrl>
          <thumbnail>1573</thumbnail>
          <bodyText><![CDATA[<p>Ever wondered how the cars stack up against each other?  Most F1 fans know pretty which car is faster than another.  The game even gets the order pretty much when it comes to the car selection screens in Time Trial and Grand Prix.</p>
<p>I've conducted my own experiment and taken each car to <a href="/{localLink:1247}" title="Shanghai">Shanghai</a> (Time Trial) for a performance shootout.  To keep everything consistent and 'scientificy', I've used the same setup in each car.  Ok, so it's possible each car would have performed better relative to others with a car setup to suit, but I needed to eliminate all but one variable, the car.   Shanghai also has really challenging first few turns which I figure can tell a lot about a cars balance (it did).</p>
<p>I didn't pay too much attention to how each car 'felt', but some cars were different enough for me to really notice, and I've taken note.</p>
<p>I don't need to ramble on, so without further ado, here's the list ordered from fastest to slowest:</p>
<p> </p>
<div class="PodBorder" style="width: 200px;">
<div class="Pod">
<table border="0" style="width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr><th width="120px">Car</th><th>Time</th></tr>
<tr>
<td>Mclaren</td>
<td>1:30.375</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Red Bull</td>
<td>1:30.857</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Ferrari</td>
<td>1:31.242</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Mercedes</td>
<td>1:31.449</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Force India</td>
<td>1:31.663</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Williams</td>
<td>1:31.805</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Renault</td>
<td>1:31.862</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Toro Rosso</td>
<td>1:32.42</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Sauber</td>
<td>1:32.50</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>HRT</td>
<td>1:33.2</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Lotus</td>
<td>1:34.6</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Virgin</td>
<td>1:34.7</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
</div>
<p> </p>
<p>Full disclosure, I ran the Lotus first, as it's my current season 1 car, so I may have got faster as I got more track time.  I generally ran about 5 laps each car, or until I was pretty happy I wasn't going to go much faster. </p>
<p>The HRT was immediately faster than the Lotus, first lap.  The Toro Rosso was the same deal. First lap in the car and I laid it's time down.  I tried another few more laps thinking I could get more pace, as it did feel alot faster than the other three.</p>
<p>I tried for a good 8 to 10 laps on the Sauber, thinking it should be faster than the Toro Rosso but I just couldn't get it to my liking. </p>
<p>My first impression of the Williams was that is fast.  I got in it and half way round the first lap I was thinking "this is going to be good". </p>
<p>The Force India was actually rather fast and I tried for a good 10 laps to beat its time with the Renault.  In the end I gave up.  The Renault just couldn't get settled on the hairpin at the end of the straight, and the first corner. </p>
<p>The Mercedes, what do I say?  I hate this car. The nose is far too high and I couldn't see the brake markers or the edge of the track. I kept running off the track, or running too much kerb and slowing down.  It did eventually prove fastest at the time though, and felt fast too. </p>
<p>Getting in the Ferrari was like getting a different race category.  It felt so much better through turns one and two. I did keep spining it on the hairpin though.</p>
<p>Red Bull. One thoughy came to my mind when I took this car out.  <strong>Traction</strong>.  This car had it in spades and damn it got through turn 1 and 2 fast.  I loved it.</p>
<p>What can I say about the best team in the world ever.  No I'm not biaised. Not even a bit.  Last up was the Mclaren, my usual car in the atomic champ and the car I play the most, so perhaps that had some impact on my times.  It hammered through turns one and two and powered past the red bull on my first lap.  I smashed it through turn 6, braking later than the Red Bull and stopping easier.  More traction down and I was edging away from the RB through T7, though the RB clawed some back at T8, which I ran wide on each time in the macca.  And it stops so well.  Turn 14, the hairpin was much easier and from there it was an easy winner.  I think there's more pace in it too, but I wanted to get this guide written tonight :)</p>]]></bodyText>
