      <Guide id="1315" parentID="1311" level="3" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1310" template="1434" sortOrder="3" createDate="2011-06-02T10:53:56" updateDate="2012-01-11T10:45:41" nodeName="Recording and editing your race with FRAPS" urlName="recording-and-editing-your-race-with-fraps" writerName="Rob Gray" creatorName="Rob Gray" path="-1,1084,1311,1315" isDoc="">
        <teaser><![CDATA[Record your race and contribute it for compilation into the highlights package, or just use it as an analysis tool for your own improvement.  Or just do like us and show off on facebook or youtube.]]></teaser>
        <author>Atomic Lambo</author>
        <authorUrl><![CDATA[]]></authorUrl>
        <thumbnail>1442</thumbnail>
        <bodyText><![CDATA[<p><span><strong>Recording</strong><br />FRAPS is the utility of choice for recording all in game footage. I won't go into details of what other things it can do, but you can read all you want about it @ www.fraps.com<br /><br /><strong>A couple things about FRAPS before you start</strong><br />You will need to have the full version of FRAPS if you wish to record anything longer than a few minutes. The demo only allows a short recording time as well as putting a watermark on it. Make sure you get the full version. Once FRAPS is installed it will do two things. It will install both the utility program, and also FRAPS's own codec. Remember that if you record on one PC and try and play your FRAPS recordings on another it won't work. It must have also have FRAPS installed so it has the codec too, you can't install it separately.<br /><br /><strong>Setup</strong><br />When you load FRAPS you'll be greeted with the following screen.<br /><img src="http://i59.photobucket.com/albums/g287/Atomic_Lambo/FRAPS.jpg" border="0" class="linked-image"/><br />It's all pretty straight forward here, but a few notes to consider.<br /><br />1.) FRAPS records in an almost RAW format and as such is very HDD intensive. It's highly recommended not to use the same drive as either your installation drive where your game is installed, or where your swap file might be located. You don't need a super fast HDD (though it helps), but it's more important to have a separate HDD. This way it will help minimize frame rate loss from any HDD thrashing.<br /><br />2.) There is no option to select which resolution to record in. That is dictated by the game resolution. You have two options, Full-size, and Half-size. Full size will mean you record at the same res as your game but will have a bigger affect on your frame-rate. Half-size will record at half resolution. IE if your running a game at full 1600 x 1200, half resolution would be 800 x 600 recording. It will also have a smaller affect on frame rate loss. F1 2010 is pretty kind on the FPS, so don't be afraid to drop the resolution, and up the quality settings to find a happy medium between image quality and a resolution you can record at with minimum frame rate loss.<br /><br />Only other options to contend with is the sound capture settings. Make sure obviously that 'Record Win7 sound' is ticked. Otherwise FRAPS will record with no sound, this option is on by default. Another option you can decide on is the external Audio input. If you want FRAPS to record any microphone or alternative sounds that might be derived from something else other than the game audio then make sure you tick this. I choose not to as it can be distracting, but up to you. Lastly, capture settings, just leave it at 30FPS. Really no need to mess with this setting. Any other settings just leave as default.<br /><br /><strong>Recording</strong><br />Once in game it's just a case of hitting the 'Video Capture Hotkey' this is generally F9 or what ever button or key you binded it to. FRAPS will keep recording till you hit the capture key again. Once you've finished recording you will fine in your specified capture directory your Fraps recordings. While the full version of FRAPS allows you to record for as long as you want, it cannot do so in just one file. So one recording session will most likely will have multiple files. The biggest file size FRAPS will use is 4GB or (3.9GB give or take). Any given recording length will depend on what settings you use in game in regards to resolution, and what settings you used in FRAPS (Full-size or Half-Size), as well as any audio settings you may have added. Generally about 2 minutes of Half-size recording at 30FPS at full HD game resolution will result in about 4GB. As such for an entire race you will need around 20-25GB's so make sure you have plenty of room before you start. <br /><br /><strong>Encoding and cutting your video</strong><br />So you've recorded your race now it's time to cut it. There are billions of programs and utilities you can use to cut your video. If you want free, the most common one is probably Microsoft Movie Maker. This used to be included with windows but is now part of the Windows Live Essentials. You can download it here: <a href="http://explore.live.com/windows-live-movie-maker?os=other" target="_blank">http://explore.live.com/windows-live-movie-maker?os=other</a><br />Personally I use Adobe Premiere Pro, which for all purposes is overkill but does give you complete control of everything.<br /><br />The way you cut your video is up to you, there is no point showing you how to do that because it will depend on what your using but I will give you these general tips.<br /><br />If your video is in 4:3/16:10/16:9 then create a video file that suits the aspect ratio. Don't encode a widescreen into 4:3 or vice versa. All you will get is a small screen with bars and your file will be unnecessarily big. Also remember that the resolution you use will affect how youtube perceives your video.<br /><br />You can encode your video in any number of formats. DivX, Xvid, h264 etc. Any of these are preferred because once your file is created it will be quite large. Personally I suggest h264. However if your using movie maker, I don't believe they offer much alternatives than the stanard AVI. You will probably then need an additional program or utility to encode your file. There are a number out there. If your using adobe premiere it will do this work for you. Otherwise there are products from Nero, Pinacle and free ones that will do the job.<br /><br />For youtube I don't recommend encoding your files larger than 350mb-400mb or else it takes quite a long time to upload. However if you have the speed and time you are free to go as large as 2GB, but I wouldn't advise that. Generally I encode two files. One at ultra high resolution for myself for viewing later, and smaller version that is suitable for youtube. If you do upload a HD version of your video, allow an extra 10 or 15 minutes by youtube to render it properly. If you play it immediately you might be convinced your video didn't upload properly. <br /></span></p>]]></bodyText>
