        <teaser><![CDATA[This document specifies the racing rules for Season 4 of the Atomic F1 championship.  ]]></teaser>
        <author>Ben Mansill - Atomic F1 Ringmaster</author>
        <authorUrl><![CDATA[]]></authorUrl>
        <thumbnail>1342</thumbnail>
        <bodyText><![CDATA[<p>This doucment specifies the rules, restrictions and operations of the AtomicF1 competition for Season 4, as developed in collaboration with the FIA respresentative, Ben Mansill, and the constructors and drivers competiting the competition.</p>
<p>All by participating in the Atomic F1 Season 4 competition, all participants have agreed to the terms of competition layed out within this document.</p>
<p>1. The Atomic F1 championship will award points for drivers and teams in accordance with the FIA F1 rules.</p>
<p>1.1 Points will be awarded for the top 10 drivers to finish the race.  First place will be awarded 25 points, second place 18 points, third place 15 points, fourth place 12 points, fifth place 10 points, sixth place 8 points, seventh place 6 points, eigth place 4 points, ninth place 2 points, tenth place 1 point.</p>
<p>1.2 In the event of a race being held with less than 10 drivers, all drivers shall be awarded points in accordance with the scheme described in section 1.3.</p>
<p>1.3 Drivers not finishing the race shall not be eligible for points.  If only 4 drivers are classified as running at the end of the race, only those four drivers shall receive points. </p>
<p>1.4 The game engine shall determine who has and has not finished the race, by denoting non finishers with DNF.</p>
<p>1.5 Drivers who are disqualified from the race are classified as non-finishers and under section 1.5 shall not be entitled to recieve points.  Disqualified drivers are denoted as DSQ</p>
<p>2. Penalties will be issued by the game engine in accordance with the FIA rules.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: line-through;">3. It has been agreed that no drivers shall use spring settings of 11 for front and back.  spring settings of 11 for either front OR back are permitted.  This holds until Codemasters has patched the issue with 11/11 springs.  Anyone found to be using 11/11 springs shall immediately forfeit their points and be disqualified from the championship and excluded from any and all future championship events.</span><br /><em>Clause 3 has been removed following the release of Path 2 for F1 2011 which fixed the springs bug.</em></p>
<p>4. Races are held on every Sunday at 2000 Sydney time.  It is the responsibility of each competitor to allow for any timezone differences including seasonal shifts such as caused by daylight savings.</p>
<p>4.1 Race start times and dates are published well in advance and it is the responsibility of each competitor to know when the race is being held.  The Atomic F1 website at www.atomicf1.com lists all upcoming races on the home page.</p>
<p>4.2 There shall be a minimal grace period before races start.  This period is generally accepted to be 15 minutes after the official race start time.  The race may start without registered competitors at this point.  Competitors should log in prior to the listed race start time for systems checks and to ensure their entry into the race event.</p>
<p>5.  Motorsport is dangerous.  It is expected that all drivers participate in a 'gentlemanly' spirit.  In accordance with the F1 FIA rules 'Racing room' shall be given. </p>
<p>5.1 Drivers shall not move off their line in the braking zone.</p>
<p>5.2 It is <em>advised</em> that all drivers losing large amounts of time per lap to an approaching driver, whether it be a fight for position or they are being lapped, should move aside and voice their intentions.  This will reduce the risk of ruining someone else's race who is clearly faster than you and probably also ruining your own race.</p>
<p>6.  Races are held at Sunday 8pm Sydney, Australia time.</p>
<p>6.1 There is one race per week.</p>
<p>6.2 Races are typically 50% distance.  100% distance specials may be used for certain events.  This will be advertised in advance.</p>
<p>6.3 There is a 15 minute grace period before the start of each race to allow people to turn up for the race.  If all registered drivers are present before 8:15, qualifying will start.</p>
<p>6.4 Qualifying will be restarted in the event of a participant suffering a connection loss.  Only one connection loss per participant will cause a restart.  If a participant suffers two connection losses they forfeit the right to participate in the race.</p>
<p>6.5 Qualifying sessions will not be restarted after 8:30pm regardless of connection losses.  After this point, any participant suffering a connection loss is unable to join the race. </p>
<p>7. Races are run on the PC platform of F1 2011</p>
<p>8.  Ben Mansill (aka Flouncy) reserves the right to adjudicate over race incidents.  All questions should be directed to him on the Atomic forums.</p>]]></bodyText>
