      <Guide id="1751" parentID="1311" level="3" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1310" template="1434" sortOrder="14" createDate="2011-11-01T12:07:14" updateDate="2012-01-11T10:45:42" nodeName="Using Telemetry with F1 2011: Getting started" urlName="using-telemetry-with-f1-2011-getting-started" writerName="Rob Gray" creatorName="Rob Gray" path="-1,1084,1311,1751" isDoc="">
        <teaser><![CDATA[A corner-stone of the "complete" F1 experience is telemetry. Despite Codemasters marketing F1 2011 as living the life of an F1 racer, and being a complete package, the game doesn't come with accessible telemetry out of the box.  Here's how to add telemetry to your F1 2011 experience.]]></teaser>
        <author>Rob Gray</author>
        <authorUrl><![CDATA[]]></authorUrl>
        <thumbnail>1752</thumbnail>
        <bodyText><![CDATA[<p>A corner-stone of the "complete" F1 experience is telemetry. Despite Codemasters marketing F1 2011 as living the life of an F1 racer, and being a complete package, the game doesn't come with accessible telemetry out of the box.  Probably to make it easy (dumb) enough for console gamers.</p>
<p>PC users don't have such limitations and there is a way to get access to telemetry data.  I noticed there is a telemetry folder for F1 2011, but the files are binary.  I went looking on the Internet...</p>
<p>I found an <a href="http://www.racedepartment.com/downloads/f1-2011-misc-102/f1-2011-data-logger-5866/">application written by kenken on the RaceDepartment site</a>.</p>
<p>I've zipped up a F1 2011 Utils folder with F1 PerfView and F1 2011 Data Logger.  Download it from <a href="/media/22535/f1-telemetry.zip">here</a>.</p>
<p> </p>
<h3>Capturing Telemetry</h3>
<p>The F1 2011 Data Logger application needs to be running while F1 2011 is running and listens via TCP for a connection from the game.  You can adjust a game config file to point to the location of kenken's data logger.</p>
<p>You need to set various settings of the logger dependant on which car and which track you're racing on.  For most the competitors of the Atomic F1 competition this won't be a problem because you'll be testing the same track in the same car all week, prior to the race.</p>
<p><img src="/media/22385/logger.png" width="310" height="322" alt="logger.png"/></p>
<p>In my case I'll always leave the Car setting as McLaren, and I'll change the GP value each week.  The other setting you need to change is the Directory. </p>
<p>Once you've done that you need to point your F1 2011 config to the logger.  To do this open the file "hardware_settings_config.xml".  This is found in your <strong>My Documents</strong> folder in the subpath <strong>./My Games/FormulaOne2011/hardwaresettings/</strong>. </p>
<p>Open the file in your favourite text editor and change the line</p>
<p><img src="/media/22363/old-telem-setting.PNG" alt="old-telem-setting.PNG"/></p>
<p>to be</p>
<p><img src="/media/22357/new-telem-setting.PNG" alt="new-telem-setting.PNG"/></p>
<p>This will redirect telemetry data to kenken's data logger.</p>
<p>Now press the <strong>Connect</strong> button to start the programme listening for a TCP connection from F1 2011.  Open your game and do as many laps as you want, and when you're done press <strong>Disconnect</strong> (the Connect button will change text once connected).  You then need to hit the <strong>Save </strong>button to save the changes to your data folder (which is included in the zip you downloaded).</p>
<p><img src="/media/22369/save-telem-data.PNG" width="163" height="29" alt="save-telem-data.PNG"/></p>
<h3>Analysing the Data</h3>
<p>Collecting this information isn't much use if there's no way to display it.  To my amazement, the tool to use is the same tool as I used for Grand Prix 2 15 years ago.  I found when I downloaded the package from the author <a href="http://rsdi.home.xs4all.nl/docs/f1perfview_doc.html">Rene Smit</a>, it didn't have the MFC71.dll included and my machine didn't have it.  Figuring most all new machines wont have this, I've included it in the above zip.  It sits in the same folder as F1PerfView.</p>
<p>To analyse some captured laps, open the tool and select <strong>Open </strong>from the menu. Change the file type filter to be <strong>All Files (*.*)</strong> and navigate to your data directory where you saved the csv files the data logger produced.</p>
<p>I like to display the Raw Lap data, the Circuit Map, and the graph.</p>
<p><img src="~/media/22307/telemetry_900x542.jpg"  width="900"  height="542" alt="telemetry.png"/></p>
<p>The next guide in this series will detail how to use telemetry and F1 Perf View to develop a car setup. Coming soon!</p>]]></bodyText>
