        <Race id="1475" parentID="1462" level="4" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1197" template="1464" sortOrder="8" createDate="2011-07-15T13:35:03" updateDate="2012-01-11T10:45:48" nodeName="Round 9 Europe" urlName="round-9-europe" writerName="Rob Gray" creatorName="Rob Gray" path="-1,1084,1458,1462,1475" isDoc="">
          <race>13</race>
          <bodyText><![CDATA[<p>Valencia saw the arrival of a new talent, ET ROM au, in an impressive debut where he finished well up the order and kept his nose clean.</p>
<p>After a dry qualifying Valencia saw the first wet race of the season and boy did it rain hard.  The first lap, with the pack bunched up, was reminiscent of Adelaide 1991 when the race was stopped at after 14 laps, and probably what it was like at Malaysia in 2009.  Visibility was near non existant as the pack slithered and slide around the track, with Flouncy pulling a 5+ second lead before half of the first lap was completed.  The pack came round to the bridge and saw Flouncy parked beside wall, probably putting his gumboots on.  From there, HolyGhost79 showed the pack the way as mistakes continued a plenty.</p>
<p>As the track dried as some were starting to think about pitting for intermediate or dry tyres, Atomic Lambo blinked first and pitted for Options.  A move that would see him capitalised on new found levels of grip, if only for a short period.  TurrbalTerror followed close behind on the same lap and pitted for intermediates, in a hope to replicate his Season 2 feats of cutting 3+ seconds a lap out of the leaders times, but it was not to be, as the inters proved worthless, with TurrbalTerror not able to replicate his full wet tyre pace of 1:45.9. </p>
<p>Atomic Lambo eventually lost his lead to Flouncy, after an inspired drive from the back of the back.  Clearly his gumboots kept his toes dry and provided the level of comfort other drivers only wished they had.</p>
<p>HolyGhost79 also pitted, but his crew fumbled his stop and put wet weather tyres back on and out he went, putting it into the wall at the first turn and forcing a re-pit, this time for dry primes.  It was enough for TurrbalTerror to get by into fourth, but not enough for  him to hold HolyGhost79 off, demonstrating why dry tryres are better than wet tyres when the sun is out.</p>
<p>Flouncy describes Valencia season 3 as his most rewarding drive ever, and with a come from last place on lap 1 to the lead, it's not hard to see why.</p>]]></bodyText>
