        <Race id="1769" parentID="1652" level="4" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1197" template="1464" sortOrder="5" createDate="2011-11-07T07:28:37" updateDate="2012-01-11T10:45:51" nodeName="Round 5 Spain" urlName="round-5-spain" writerName="Rob Gray" creatorName="Rob Gray" path="-1,1084,1458,1652,1769" isDoc="">
          <race>66</race>
          <bodyText><![CDATA[<p>Round 5 at the Catalunya circuit in Spainish city of Barcelona saw the McLarens lock out the front row of the grid for the second race in succession.  TurrbalTerror held provisional pole for a good part of the session until bobaj0r eclipsed the time by a few hundredths, a simlar margin to last weekends Turkish Grand Prix.  The surprise result was Atomic Lambo back in fifth position, although this may have been better if the qualifying session hadn't been restarted.</p>
<p>When the race eventually started, the McLarens made a clean getaway at the front, both utilising the KERS get away quick, with TurrbalTerror riding bobaj0r's gearbox before backing off to avoid any potential first corner incidents, to be immediately swamped by a hard charge Atomic Lambo, with massive top end speed, Eradicator84, ET_Rom and an opportunistic Flouncy, making the most of the first corner melee.</p>
<p><strong>1st - bobaj0r - McLaren<br /></strong>Drove a clean race from pole position after narrowly beating his teammate.  Was troubled initially by Flouncy but able to capitalise on small mistake by the Ferrari driver.  He was kept honest by Atomic Lambo and Flouncy.</p>
<p>There's no question now that bobaj0r is the real deal. Another controlled and dominating drive from the McLaren driver he may have only pipped his team mate to pole by only a few hundredths of a second but from the get go he was unstoppable. He handled the pressure from Ferrari's Flouncy on the opening laps, and when he came out of the pits on his last stint just in front of Lambo controlled his pace while his tires came up to temp and drove away from the pack. If it looked easy from the cockpit it's probably because it was. Three wins now from four starts and a worst of second the McLaren driver is riding a wave of confidence that boads well for him going into the next race and a loud warning to his rivals. Will look to set records now and join a select group of drivers that have one three consecutive races.</p>
<p><strong>2nd - Atomic Lambo - Renault<br /></strong>His job was made harder by starting from fifth on the grid but was able to power past a few cars before turn 1.  Survived a messy first lap to finish the lap in 3rd place.  Ran an option, option, prime strategy to try and close down bobaj0r.  He ran the McLaren driver close in the final stages.</p>
<p>Not the easiest weekend for the Renault driver, he suffering from traffic in qualifying and only managed to put his Renault 5th on the grid. Pre-race testing suggested pole was on the cards however he had an excellent start on the grippy side of the grid and worked his way up to 2nd before the first corner. However lost out badly slipping to 7th at one stage during the opening corners. He recovered will before the end of the first lap to get back to third after a stunning double pass on the straight however by then the leaders were several seconds down the road. Switched to an alternative strategy to try and leap frog the Ferrari in the pits, and almost managed to do the same to the McLaren. However 2nd and some solid points, and with more favoured tracks coming up, Lambo is in a good position to challenge bobaj0r.</p>
<p><strong>3rd - Flouncy - Ferrari</strong><br />Made a good start, getting the holeshot at the first corner and taking second place.  Flouncy lacked outright pace for the race win and was challenged by the second McLaren of TurrbalTerror for third, before fuel delivery problems for the McLaren #2 saw him drop off.</p>
<p>Challenged the McLaren during the opening laps but a small mistake and quickly degrading tires saw him fall back as the Renault of Lambo caught up with him. Will rue staying out too long during his first stint as the Renault jumped him in the pits. Relatively strong drive he held off a fast finishing TurrbalTerror in the sister McLaren to round out the podium. A strong result considering the last race in Istanbul but will be disappointed it wasn't at least another step higher. He'll be buoyed by the good pace he showed in practice and will want to carry that over to Monaco, a place that he has won at before.<br /><br /></p>
<p><strong>4th - HolyGhost79 - Lotus<br /></strong>Yet another solid drive from the Lotus leader.  He started from the back of the pack after not participating in qualify, fearing a break in the space-time continuum, but climbed up through the field. Capitalised on the misfortune a few in front to secure a solid fourth place. </p>
<p>Strangely didn't set a time in qualifying, opting to save his tires for the race and started from 12th on the grid. Drove a fairly conservative race and kept mainly out of trouble. Was fortunate to steal 4th with TurrbalTerrors refuelling issues, but nevertheless a good drive and hopefully plenty of positives to take into Monaco.<br /><br /></p>
<p><strong>5th - ET ROM au - Mercedes<br /></strong>Qualified well, in fourth, and made a good start but was tagged by NightKid2, placing him to the back of the pack.  Climbed up the field with a consistent drive, but was tagged and spun again by NightKid2.  Lacked outright pace to challenge for the win, but would have made fourth spot if not for the incidents.</p>
<p>Unfortunate not to be higher, the Mercedes driver was competitive all weekend and after putting his car on the second row of the grid. Made a decent start but was caught up in the mayhem of turn 10 with contact with NightKid2. Tangled with him later again in the race and dropped further down the pack. Will take some consolidation in the fact that the Sauber driver was penalised a race for this conduct but will be overall disappointed with what could have been a top 4 or more drive.</p>
<p><strong>6th - NightKid2 - Sauber<br /></strong>Qualified well but was given a 10 place penalty forcing him to start from the back.  Drove an aggressive race and made good places up at the opening lap, but frequent mistakes hurt his overall performance.  He set the fastest lap on his way to his best result of the season.  Unfortunately he also earned a one race suspension on the grounds of continued aggressive driving.</p>
<p>Was the centre of a number of controversial passes and moves which in the end cost him a grid spot in this weeks Monaco GP. Despite being extreamly quick and setting the faster lap in race the Sauber driver tangled with a number of other drivers leading to the governing body and stewards to disqualify him from the next race. Showed great single lap pace, but needs to combine that with patience and racecraft that is sure to come with experience.<br /><br /></p>
<p><strong>7th - TurrbalTerror - McLaren<br /></strong>Again qualified well, in second place, hundredths off pole.  Had another poor start after getting off the line.  Received a drive through penalty for an illegal overtake on turn 7 of lap 1, after putting a wheel on the grass when passing Eradicator84.  Drove well from the back of the grid to be up to fourth by lap 12 and into third by lap 26 and getting to within 10 seconds of the leader.  Ran out of fuel 1 lap before the end, dropping him from a clear fourth to seventh.</p>
<p>Had the pace to challenge for the win, all be it if it wasn't for a drive through penalty received during the opening lap. Some say warranted but it could be easily argued that it was quite harsh. However in testament to his character he kept his cool and put in a great drive to work his way back through the field to almost snatch 3rd from the Ferrari of Flouncy. However a fual management issue caused him to lose a number of places as the McLaren crawled around the track for the last lap and a half. A weekend to forget.</p>
<p><strong>8th - roxas3sora3 - Virgin<br /></strong>Drove a quiet race from 8th on the grid, into 8th position when the flag fell.  Never had the podium challenging pace, but none-the-less drove a solid race.</p>
<p>Will be slightly disappointed with the result but showed strong race pace. Remained relatively out of trouble and showed some good consistent pace. Will want to score strongly in Monaco to ensure he stays in front of the second Renault and stay within striking distance of the much improved Williams.</p>
<p><strong>9th - BreakerMorant - Ferrari<br /></strong>The veteran of the field once again put in a points scoring drive, rising from 10th to 9th, albiet 3 laps down, and giving Ferrari a few more precious points.</p>
<p>Was well off the times during qualifying but found a better pace during the race. Lost alot of time getting out of the way to blue flags but overall an ok race for the Ferrari driver. Will need to make sure that he's scoring more points in Monaco as Ferrari slip further behind Renault and McLaren.</p>
<p><strong>DSQ - st8smn350<br /></strong>Qualified in 11th and car troubles forces his retirement before he had a chance to show his potential.  Would have been inline for a points finish today.</p>
<p><strong>DSQ - Eradicator84<br /></strong>Drove assertively off the line and into 2nd place for a brief instant before third.  Got tagged by ET rom and NightKid on turn 5 of lap 1, and by TurrbalTerror on turn 6.  Lacked ultimate pace to lead the mid-field.  Officials disqualified him for reasons unknown.</p>
<p><strong>DSQ - Fredzfrog</strong><br />Qualified in the top 10 but failed to make the race start.</p>
<p><strong>DSQ - Modz85</strong><br />Again let down by equipment problems and failed to set a qualifying time or join the race.  Hopefully his car is in better shape for the Monaco grand prix next week.</p>]]></bodyText>
