            <umbBlogPost id="1333" parentID="1334" level="6" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1053" template="1046" sortOrder="1" createDate="2011-06-06T07:49:16" updateDate="2012-01-11T10:46:14" nodeName="Valencia Season 3 Results" urlName="valencia-season-3-results" writerName="Rob Gray" creatorName="Rob Gray" path="-1,1084,1057,1079,1306,1334,1333" isDoc="">
              <closeComments>0</closeComments>
              <PostDate>2011-06-06T07:52:00</PostDate>
              <metaTitle>
              </metaTitle>
              <metaKeywords><![CDATA[]]></metaKeywords>
              <metaDescription><![CDATA[]]></metaDescription>
              <thumbnail>
              </thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>Valencia saw the arrival of a new talent, ET ROM au, in an impressive debut where he finished well up the order and kept his nose clean.</p>
<?UMBRACO_MACRO type="Qualifying" macroAlias="F1InlineRace" raceid="13" />
<p> </p>
<p>After a dry qualifying Valencia saw the first wet race of the season and boy did it rain hard.  The first lap, with the pack bunched up, was reminiscent of Adelaide 1991 when the race was stopped at after 14 laps, and probably what it was like at Malaysia in 2009.  Visibility was near non existant as the pack slithered and slide around the track, with Flouncy pulling a 5+ second lead before half of the first lap was completed.  The pack came round to the bridge and saw Flouncy parked beside wall, probably putting his gumboots on.  From there, HolyGhost79 showed the pack the way as mistakes continued a plenty.</p>
<p>As the track dried as some were starting to think about pitting for intermediate or dry tyres, Atomic Lambo blinked first and pitted for Options.  A move that would see him capitalised on new found levels of grip, if only for a short period.  TurrbalTerror followed close behind on the same lap and pitted for intermediates, in a hope to replicate his Season 2 feats of cutting 3+ seconds a lap out of the leaders times, but it was not to be, as the inters proved worthless, with TurrbalTerror not able to replicate his full wet tyre pace of 1:45.9. </p>
<p>Atomic Lambo eventually lost his lead to Flouncy, after an inspired drive from the back of the back.  Clearly his gumboots kept his toes dry and provided the level of comfort other drivers only wished they had.</p>
<p>HolyGhost79 also pitted, but his crew fumbled his stop and put wet weather tyres back on and out he went, putting it into the wall at the first turn and forcing a re-pit, this time for dry primes.  It was enough for TurrbalTerror to get by into fourth, but not enough for  him to hold HolyGhost79 off, demonstrating why dry tryres are better than wet tyres when the sun is out.</p>
<?UMBRACO_MACRO type="Race" macroAlias="F1InlineRace" raceid="13" />
<p>Flouncy describes Valencia season 3 as his most rewarding drive ever, and with a come from last place on lap 1 to the lead, it's not hard to see why.</p>
<?UMBRACO_MACRO utubewidth="" utubevideo="PIXOkmQOte0" utubeheight="" macroAlias="uTube.ChromelessPlayer" />
<p> </p>]]></content>
              <tags><![CDATA[]]></tags>
            </umbBlogPost>
            <umbBlogPost id="1335" parentID="1334" level="6" writerID="0" creatorID="0" nodeType="1053" template="1046" sortOrder="2" createDate="2011-06-06T07:50:44" updateDate="2012-01-11T10:46:14" nodeName="British GP season 3 results" urlName="british-gp-season-3-results" writerName="Rob Gray" creatorName="Rob Gray" path="-1,1084,1057,1079,1306,1334,1335" isDoc="">
              <closeComments>0</closeComments>
              <PostDate>2011-06-06T07:52:00</PostDate>
              <metaTitle>
              </metaTitle>
              <metaKeywords><![CDATA[]]></metaKeywords>
              <metaDescription><![CDATA[]]></metaDescription>
              <thumbnail>
              </thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>It was clear from the off that Flouncy meant business at Silverstone.  His pole time of 1:31.085 stands as the fastest lap we've yet seen of this circuit at a race meet and was significantly faster than second placed HolyGhost79. This gird had a larger spread that the previous few races.</p>
<p> </p>
<?UMBRACO_MACRO type="Qualifying" macroAlias="F1InlineRace" raceid="14" />
<p> </p>
<p>Race day threw up another doozie, with heavy rain yet again.  Flouncy made a clean start as the pack slipped and slid through the first few corners, battling over minor positions.  The end of lap 1 was exciting, as HolyGhost79, bobaj0r, and TurrbalTerror all jockeyed for 2nd position coming out of the last corner.  bobaj0r got squeezed by HolyGhost79 into TurrbalTerror as HolyGhost79 past TurrbalTerror, but both went off on turn 1 of lap 2 and bobaj0r was back in second place before his own mistakes cost him a higher finish.</p>
<p>TurrbalTerror lost more and more ground over the first five laps as he drove clean off the track on more corners than not, losing out a whooping gap of 45 seconds to bobaj0r in fourth place.  It was a gap that was to stay consistent until the end of the race.</p>
<p>Flouncy had his own misfortune when his steering dettached from the cockpit and he was lucky to salvage fourth place in front of a luckless Atomic Lambo who was forced to pull off track to take answer his phone.  Maybe Force India will invest in a handsfree before the next event. Although driving whilst talking on the phone is not against FIA regulations.</p>
<p>The misfortunes of two of the leading front runners was the fortunes of the fans, as it enabled the chasing pack to close up in points, but HolyGhost79 to extend his points lead ever so marginally.  Fortunately over the whole weekend, Flouncy and HolyGhost both had finished in P1 and P4, with only qualifying points difference the decider, and that swung in second place Flouncy's direction.</p>
<?UMBRACO_MACRO type="Race" macroAlias="F1InlineRace" raceid="14" />
<p> </p>
<?UMBRACO_MACRO utubewidth="" utubevideo="kA1ypKyYCxw" utubeheight="" macroAlias="uTube.ChromelessPlayer" />
<p> </p>
<p> </p>]]></content>
