              <teaser><![CDATA[Championships are built on the aspirations of many.  It doesn’t matter if you’re the next hot thing or a multiple world champion, everyone starts the season on zero points and maximum potential.  19 races across the globe and months later, there can by only one champion]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p><img src="~/media/5226/trophies_285x400.jpg"  width="285"  height="400" alt="trophies.jpg" style="float: right;"/></p>
<p>Championships are built on the aspirations of many.  It doesn’t matter if you’re the next hot thing or a multiple world champion, everyone starts the season on zero points and maximum potential.  19 races across the globe and months later, there can by only one champion.  Victory is the reward of the brave, the cunning, and the most importantly the fast.  In a sport where fractions of a second makes the differences between winner and also-ran, split second decisions at seemingly random times are often the differentiator.</p>
<p>Before Season 3 was underway we had the 12 strong entrants: Flouncy, Atomic Lambo, HolyGhost79, TurrbalTerror, bobaj0r, Fredzfrog, OriginalBollum, Hulkster, CrusierComet, BreakerMorant, Krispy89, roxas3sora3.  Not all of those saw the opening race, and some never made the grid, other joined the competition later on, while others left early.  From race one in Bahrain it was clear the order would not change significantly.  The fast group remained, thinned slightly by the lack of Eradicator84 and the non-starting bobaj0r.  Flouncy, Atomic Lambo, HolyGhost79, and TurrbalTerror all stake a claim for ultimate victory in Season 3. </p>
<p>Tensions rose early on as intentions, punctuated by aggressive actions were made clear by the various would-be champions.  After the first four races it was looking that HolyGhost79 was clear favourite to win.  His race consistency was proving hard to beat and the championship was looking beyond reach of all but Flouncy by the midway point.  Flouncy’s four wins on the trot and strong qualifying performance gave him maximum points and before we knew it he was leading the title race.  Had HolyGhost79 cracked under pressure?  Had the normally ice cold driver started to fall apart when it mattered?  HolyGhost79 proved his naysayers wrong in Korea with an emphatic pole and race win, but Flouncy retaliated with the same in Brazil.  The field of would-be’s whittled down to one ‘already is’ and another ‘should be’. </p>
<p>Abu Dhabi is a track neither contender has won on or achieved pole on before.  It is the stomping ground of third place Atomic Lambo.   This season both contenders come from Group Force India and do not have the luxury of using their teammate as a foil to their opposition. </p>
<p>What does this mean?  It means that Abu Dhabi <strong>must</strong> be about pure speed and talent.  The finishing position in this race will determine whether we have a dual world champion or a new world champion.  It’s also a race about the non-contenders.  Where will their allegiances lie?  Have deals already been made for favours?  Will title runners #3 and #4 finish the race in positions #1 and #2.</p>
<p>They say victory favours the brave. They say victory favours the fortunate.  They say victory favours the strong.</p>
<p>Well,  i say victory will only be for the driver that has all three.  This is not kids play.  This is the finale of season 3 of the Atomic f1 championship.</p>]]></content>
