              <teaser><![CDATA[Atomic F1's double champion dishes the dirt on what makes him tick, what's in store for his teammate, and how we can go about beating him in Season 4]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>First of all, congratulations on wrapping up your second title under such strong opposition. Many didn't rate you a chance at the halfway point. Lets get straight into it shall we</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong> What was the turning point in your season and what made you believe you could catch your teammate in equal machinery?</strong></p>
<p><em>As the season ran through its first half Ghost was steadily building a lead, but I thought things would somehow magically balance out – my goal was to be in contention near the end, along with at least one other front runner, preferably more, but I underestimated just how strong out of the gate Ghost was as the season started, and how consistent he’d be. </em></p>
<p><em><br /></em></p>
<p><em>Heading into Valencia - that was the start of my more motivated try-harder campaign to get some points balance back. I realised that track was the make or break point in the season for me and I really needed to close the gap.</em></p>
<p><em><br /></em></p>
<p><em>I was pretty pumped up about winning that one – because, of the following three races (Silverstone, Germany and Hungary) I reckoned I’d be able to win Silverstone and Hungary, and that’d bring things back to relative equilibrium.</em></p>
<p> </p>
<p><em>I got Valencia, but bloody Ghost then went on to win all three of the following rounds. That fightback of his, plus the thrill I was still on from pushing and really wanting it at Valencia, and getting that one, gave me a real kick in the pants. So after Ghosty had shot ahead with his hat trick I looked at the numbers and realised I’d pretty much have to win six of the next (and last) seven races.</em></p>
<p> </p>
<p><em>The only one I was relatively sure of was Suzuka. The rest was a real battle and really really exciting as it progressed. It made the racing so much more involving, tense, a bit emotional and as the wins came in I couldn’t relax. I felt just like a real racer, and that was neat. </em><br /><br /></p>
<p><strong>You've had a number of brilliant victories over the course of your championship. Which was the most rewarding? </strong><br /><br /><em>Totally Valencia. It had real ‘story’ and drama. After my off at the start I really had to dig deeper than ever before and drive fast, and perfectly. Discovered I quite liked that super-concentration, so was able to take that Zen to the rest of the season. I love that circuit but it’s one where everyone is pretty evenly matched. I liked that win also because I showed myself I could take it to Ghost in the rain.</em><br /><br /><br /><strong>The season has been long and stressful, how do you plan to celebrate your victory?</strong></p>
<p><em>Think I might dive into a big arse RPG, or some Civ 5, maybe some Total War – the opposite of racing, some nice peaceful turn-based gaming where a few beers actually improve my skills :} And some mountainbiking. And less ice cream.</em></p>
<p><br /><br /><strong>You are now the most successful driver in the history of atomic f1, and nearly the oldest.  How will you keep motivated for another campaign.</strong><br /><br />The season and how it plays out will take care of that. I actually wanted Ghost to win the championship this time – I was only really chasing the points battle cos that part of it was fun, the whole coming from behind thing. But of course the win feels pretty good. Commiserations to Ghost, he’s an amazing driver, a top bloke and a real gent on the track.<br /><br /><em>So next time I’ll just enjoy the ebb and flow of the racing. Hopefully there’ll be a bigger grid, and we’re all so bloody good at this now some really close racing is on the cards, and that’s great.</em><br /><br /><em>Also, hopefully F1 2011 will have improved handling, so it’s a nice refresher for everyone to re-learn the cars, and see how we all stack up against each other with that.</em><br /><br /><br /><strong>It is rumored next season will see the mandatory pairing of a "fast" and "slow" driver. This will see the championship winning Group Force India team broken up.  Who do you think you teammate HolyGhost79 should team with? </strong><br /><em>Fredz. It’s only natural. They have a magnetic attraction for each other’s cars on the track.</em><br /><br /><br />Finally, there are a number of new drivers on the grid this season, and with expansion plans in place, the Atomic F1 Championship will likely see new blood injected as the new regulations and car specifications come into play. <br /><br /><strong>What advice have you got for new drivers wanting to hone their skills and one day challenging for the top spot?</strong><br /><br /><em>Just do a practice session before the race. I do one 40% GP against AI on the Sunday and that’s enough, along with as many practice laps as needed to feel good with the setup. Time Trial teaches bad habits, avoid it.</em><br /><br /><em>Learn how and where to overtake on each track, and be able to take a corner various ways to give you the flexibility to overtake – and vice versa – know where you’re vulnerable. </em><br /><br /><em>Drive to survive. Don’t out-pace yourself. Know which corners in a race are the danger ones where you’re more likely to come off, and get those right. If need be tailor your car setup around making sure just those corners can be done with better odds of doing them cleanly.</em><br /><br /><em>Just learn the car. Once you’re fully Zenned with how the car handles, you can tackle any track and it becomes about carving fractions of seconds out as you improve, and that’s always a real joy.</em></p>
<p> </p>
<p>There you have it.  Dual atomic F1 champion Flouncy give us some insight into what makes him tick and how we might one day wrest that title from him.  Thanks Flouncy and have an enjoyable off-season.</p>]]></content>
