              <teaser><![CDATA[Final agreement on the season 4 points system has nearly been reached and should be ready soon, says new commercial rights holder Flouncy]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p><img src="~/media/6044/math_400x267.jpg"  width="400"  height="267" alt="math.jpg" style="float: right;"/>After taking over the commercial rights to the atomic f1 championsihp from previous owner Lambo, a number of refinements have been made to the running of atomic f1.  Not least is the system by which points are awarded to drivers.</p>
<p>Under the existing system points are awarded for both qualifying and race. The top 5 qualifiers being awarded 5 points down to 1 for finishing 1st through 5th. Race points are awarded from from 1st down to 10th, with 25, 18, 15, 12, 10, 8, 6, 4, 2, 1 being the points awarded. </p>
<p>One of the issues raised in recent FOTA/Flouncy discussions was the points gap between the top 4 and the rest of the pack.  While the top 4 generally did compete in more races than the the rest of the field, the awarding of points for qualifying has been cited as one of the reasons why the gap between the top 4 and the rest was so high. </p>
<p>Historically the reward of pole position was the best starting position, and the best opportunity to win the race especially on tracks where overtaking is possible.  However, in recent years overtaking has been generally much easier to do and the intrisic value of pole position diminished.  The awarding of points provided new motivation for drivers to perform on Saturday instead of parking it in the garage through qaulifying. </p>
<p>However, now the performance between the field is once again contracting, the rewarding of points for qualifying has again been raised.  New commercial rights holder, Flouncy's, who together with the FIA, after consdiering from FOTA has the final say in what the new structure will be.  Flouncy's latest draft has the points system returning to the more traditional, without qualifying points, and a 25, 18, 15, 12, 10, 8, 6, 4, 2, 1 structure from 1st down through to 10th.</p>
<p>However, with the deadline date for the points system not until the start of October there is still plenty of time for FOTA to lodge an appeal.  Also, the FIA doesn't release it's new, F1 2011 operating framework until September 23, where some of the decisions being made today may be overruled.</p>]]></content>
