              <metaTitle>
              </metaTitle>
              <metaKeywords><![CDATA[Williams, practice, testing, eradicator84, roxas3sora3]]></metaKeywords>
              <metaDescription><![CDATA[Both Williams drivers extracted maximum performance from their cars for Sunday's Grand Prix.  Williams are looking to lead the constructors standings.]]></metaDescription>
              <thumbnail>1418</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[Both Williams drivers extracted maximum performance from their cars for Sunday's Grand Prix.  Williams are looking to lead the constructors standings.]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p><img src="~/media/5232/williams-car_400x272.jpg"  width="400"  height="272" alt="williams-car.jpg" style="float: right;"/>It's a dry sunny Friday afternoon here at Sepang. I'm on the grass here at the entrance of the pit lane to speak with a couple of team Williams' most important leaders. Sam Michael, Williams Technical Chief and Sir Frank Williams, Williams Team Principal.<br /><br />I met with Sam first to talk about how both Williams drivers, roxa3sora3 and Eradicator84 put in some good testing hours and came out of it with a nice surprise.</p>
<p><br /><em>"Based on our practice session runs we know for a fact that both drivers will beat last years fastest qualifying lap time." </em>said Sam, <em>"And we're not talking by a few tenths either. Based on our on-track data and simulations both drivers will easily surpass that time by several seconds each. So we're looking for a solid race from both drivers to bring maximum points in for the team on Sunday".</em><br /><br />When I asked about the notorious wet weather situation that often occurs at Sepang Sam replied, <em>"We're not too worried about a deluge this year, all forecasts indicate good weather on the day, but as you know that can change at a moments notice. If there's no rain on Saturday we might have to put the drivers into the simulators to get them comfortable with the new cars on a wet track. In fact..."</em> he said pointing to the sky behind me. I looked and there was some rather ominous looking clouds to the south east of the track. I turned around to finish our interview but Sam was already running back down the pit lane in a hurry, so I guess they've still got some work to do.<br /><br />I then met with Sir Frank Williams, who has made the effort to come to Sepang this year, to catch up and to clarify a few rumours floating around.<br /><br />"Sir Frank, I can call you that can't I?"<br /><em>"Please, call me Uncle Frank, we're all in the F1 family here"</em> he said smiling.</p>
<p>"Ok 'Uncle Frank' you don't often get out to tracks these days due to your health, what made you decide to come out for this race meeting?"<br /><em>"Well my wife Ginny has been nagging me to get out of the house so I thought I'd come and support the team in person this weekend. That and I wanted to test out my new wheel chair."</em></p>
<p>"So has any of this paraphernalia you've got here have anything to do with it too?"<br /><em>"Actually yes. My son Jonathan managed to get me this great team coloured automated cheering system attached to my chair. These pom poms are attached to these rotating articulated mechanical arms here on my wheel chair" he explained, pointing to the long spindly metal rods jutting up from either side of his wheel chair with blue and white pom poms attached to the end of them, "so when I'm watching from the side of the track I can push this big blue button here and the chair does all the cheering for me! How brilliant is that!?"</em></p>
<p>"That IS pretty neat!"<br /><em>"That's not the best bit though, see this container on the back on by wheel chair?"</em></p>
<p>"Yes"<br /><em>"This contains our experimental new KERS system"</em></p>
<p>"Really? It's quite small!"<br /><em>"Indeed, I plan to test it out on Sunday at the start of the race."</em></p>
<p>"Huh?"<br /><em>"SHHHHH, keep it a secret. I'll be on the grid along with everyone else getting the cars ready for the race then when the cars go for their warm up lap I'll sneak back to the start of pit lane and wait for the safety car to pull up behind all the cars just before race start and drive over into his blind spot so he won't know I'm there. Then, when the race starts I'll flip this red switch here" pointing to an aircraft style switch with flip up protector on his right arm rest "and the KERS will activate and I'll race down the main straight to see how well our new system works! I might even deploy my cheering system at the same time to motivate our two drivers faster down the main straight at the start!"</em></p>
<p>"Umm, isn't that dangerous and against FIA rules?"<br /><em>"Shh! Keep your voice down!" he whispered loudly, looking around to see if anyone was watching us "Look with the amount of testing allowed by teams this year we have to be 'creative' in how, when and where we do our testing. I've spoken with Bernie and he loved the idea! He even bet I could beat the two HRTs to the first corner! But said I should keep it low key until the surprise moment."</em></p>
<p>"Oook then, well good luck with it"<br /><em>"Thanks it's going to be a hoot!"</em></p>
<p>"I wanted to ask you about the rumours of both your drivers being spotted in the McLaren and Red Bull garages today. What's that all about?"<br /><em>"Oh yeah there's a fancy new Xbox game the drivers all talking about, it's called '1102 1F' or something, you know how kids are these days, gotta play with the latest craze"</em></p>
<p>"So the fact that we saw both McLaren and Red Bull cars drive around the track today with their drivers wearing Soras and Marks helmets is just an accident or something?"<br /><em>"Yes... like I said... testing.. craze.. c-r-e-a-t-i-v-e"</em><br /><br />At this point his face was getting redder and redder and voice louder and louder, ranting on until he swivelled his chair around 180 degrees, flipped the red switch and in a burst of sound and grass debree was speeding back towards the Williams garage.</p>
<p><br />I'm not sure what what will happen now but the Williams drivers will have a good reason to get off to a quick start in Sundays race. Should be exciting!</p>]]></content>
