              <metaKeywords><![CDATA[]]></metaKeywords>
              <metaDescription><![CDATA[]]></metaDescription>
              <thumbnail>1717</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[Jonathan Leggard offers his unique insight into this weekends fourth Shanghai Atomic F1 GP.]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p><strong>Will there be a Shanghai surprise?</strong><br />We've had two races on two very different circuits in Formula One 2011 so far with two different winners. However going into round 3 of the Atomic F1 championship the leading driver hasn't won a race yet. Lambo leads the championship by 5 points despite not winning either round, but thanks two consistant 2nd place finishes. The good news for neutrals is that, thanks to the new regulations and Pirelli tyres, plenty of wheel-to-wheel action has ensured Sunday afternoons remain unmissable. But it's also true that 2010 was one of the best seasons in recent years because of a four-way competition for the top spot in the championship, and if we are to see a repeat this season, McLaren, Ferrari, Lotus and Renault need a return to the top step of the podium sooner rather than later. Will China deliver the first twist in the 2011 championship tale? <br /><br /><strong>In form:</strong><br />Such was bobaj0rs dominance at Sepang not even a spin could stop him from taking the chequered flag in record race time. Last year bobaj0r struggled with bad luck in the opening rounds but this season looks especially promising. If Ghost winning at China last season was the jolt the championship needed then, than Bobaj0r winning at China will send bolts of lightning through the field. His odds have improved imeserabily.<br /><br /><br /><strong>Out of form:</strong><br />It was his worst race to date and probably much of it through no fault of his own, but theres no deneying that after his win in Melbourne, Flouncy didn't look like the dominate self in Sepang. Qualified poorly due to reliability issues his race was compromised from the first corner taking a spin and then suffering from a puncture later on. Managed to recover to a respectable 7th however the Ferrari driver will see that as a disaster. Will probably bounce back however Flouncy has never won here at China. <br /><br /><strong>One to watch:</strong><br />If Ghost last season was the shot in the arm the championship needed, then bobaj0r is like a lighting strike. Didn't compete in Melbourne, but rocked up to the second round in Sepang and set the timesheets on fire. Looking just as dangerous at China bobaj0r has leaped into championship contention.<br /><br /><strong>Talking points:</strong><br />The Drag Reduction System - For years F1 observers have complained that there is not enough overtaking in the sport. But now that a system has boosted the chances of wheel-to-wheel racing it is labelled as fake, with critics saying that the FIA dictates where the drivers overtake. Although true, it can be argued that it only enhances the existing overtaking areas and one place dictated by the FIA is better than nothing at all. Perhaps the biggest concern should be the complexity of the system (it can only be used when a driver is within a second of the car in front at a certain point on the track, but not in the first two laps after the start or a safety car … and not at all in the wet). For the casual viewer it makes an already complex sport even harder to understand. <br /><br /><strong>Fast facts:</strong><br />- This will be the 4th Chinese GP in Atomic F1 history. S1 - Eradicator, S2/S3 Ghost<br />- Qualifying record: Flouncy 1:33.484<br />- The circuit plan is designed to look like the Chinese character 'Shang', which means high or above.<br /><br /><br /><strong>The circuit:</strong><br />The Shanghai International Circuit is another new-generation F1 track designed by the ubiquitous Hermann Tilke. Unlike some of his other creations, the track does have some in-built character, such as team offices built on stilts over water and the impressive bridges over the pit straight - all built at a cost of US$459 million. On track there is a mix of high speed corners, long straights and big stops, requiring medium to high downforce levels. Overtaking is possible and the most likely location is at turn 13 where the cars brake from 200mph to 45mph after a 0.7 mile straight. Another notable feature on the track includes the 270 degree turn one that requires the cars to hit two apices before being spat out in the opposite direction in turn two. <br /><br /><strong>Betting:</strong><br />After his explosive win in Sepang it's time to get on the bobaj0r freight train. Bobaj0r 3/1, Flouncy 5/1, Lambo 7/1, Ghost now slips to 20/1. Worth putting an each way bet on ET-Rom, 18/1.<br /><br /><strong>Leggard prediction:</strong><br />If bobaj0r repeats his exploits at Sepang, he'll not only be the next races favourite, but most probably the next championship favourite.</p>]]></content>
