              <thumbnail>1210</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[Mark Fogerty interviews roxas3sora3 and shares a rare insight into the up-and-coming talent.]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>"Just some Japanese green tea thanks." That was how simple roxas3sora3 was towards the waitress as we sat down in the Williams motorhome. After said drink appeared, we got on with the business of talking to one of the rare Asian drivers in this competition. After what was a promising start, I had to figure out what was going wrong with the man that is the steady rock of Williams F1.<br /><br />"Melbourne was probably one of the most memorable tracks really so I wanted something special of it. Going 4th and holding off a fast charging Ghost would be the highlight of my life." And the lowlights?<br /><br />"Well, I suppose the last round (Malaysia). We had a fantastic qualifying and were quite set to capitalise with our run. Then everything had to go pear shape. Kids at the back with no experience, they had to go and screw everything up for the rest of us." This was coming from a man that had been quite soft spoken about the new drivers of the competition. He didn't seemed fazed that implications of his spin came from these drivers. With that, I decided to speak to him about what happened in China after such a great qualifying session.<br /><br />"It was interesting as everyone expected rain on one qualifying and we got it here in China." In torrential conditions, roxas3sora3 managed to post the pole lap before sliding down the field. "That was one surprise as I expected everyone to hit very low 1:40s. So to be on pole for a second was good to savour but it wasn't meant to be." After in which, he finished qualifying in 7th which gives him the best qualifying position in the wet. "I'm still learning how to be fast in the wet. As long as I'm improving, then it should be interesting."<br /><br />However, all that good work in qualifying was undone instantly at turn 3. "Turn 3 to 4 was probably where I lost the battle in the midfield. I was on the racing line when the Red Bull (presumably st8smn) came alongside and argued over that position. I kept my stance and only it was when he started to push me off the line that I had to back out. If I didn't, I would have ended up with a broken wing. That single instant was when I lost the midfield battle. And it was frustrating to see him go and then lose that position so easily (after a few turns, roxas3sora3 kept in sight of the two cars, Red Bull and Saber before both lost it) didn't make me feel that he's ready for F1. I think whoever it is, he's not a racer, he's just a menace." Harsh words from a man that advocates gentlemanly racing but given his frustration and as well as the results, it is easy to see.<br /><br />But, were there any positives from that race? "Positives for me showed that I can mix it up with the midfield and get close to the top tier. All I have to do is be consistent and pounce on any chance to be better. Simple as that." And this racer will be interesting to watch as his strategies and excellent thinking made him one of the drivers that could easily be a no.1 driver.</p>]]></content>
