              <thumbnail>1623</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[When Atomic F1 turned up at the gates of the Circuit de Catalunya last season the Lotus of Ghost had already taken out 3 of the first 5 races, and finished no lower than second.  This season it's a very different story, with 4 races down, and 3 different winners, the top 4 drivers are separated by only 19 points.]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>When Atomic F1 turned up at the gates of the Circuit de Catalunya last season the Lotus of Ghost had already taken out 3 of the first 5 races, and finished no lower than second.  This season it's a very different story, with 4 races down, and 3 different winners, the top 4 drivers are separated by only 19 points.  It would be a brave person who would place a bet on the end season champion, and with at least 4 drivers within a win of each other, it's anyone's bet on who will take the chequered flag in Spain.  The outcome of this race will tell us a lot about what we can expect from the rest of the season, both from a competition and entertainment point of view. <br /><br /><strong>On form:</strong><br />Bobaj0r has stamped his title ambitions with a measured drive in Istanbul and with his worst finish so far a 2nd at China. If it weren't for the missed race in Melbourne there's no doubt the lead would be more than just 7 points. Lambo will be hot on his tale to reel in the small lead after the Istanbul GP, but with momentum and confidence on Bobaj0r's side it's clear he will be the one to beat in Spain.<br /><br /><strong>Out of form:</strong><br />Not long ago we would have said a 2 race slump would be a rarity for Ferrari's Flouncy, but after a disappointing 4th at Istanbul many are asking is the magic that lead to a stunning comeback in Season 3 and a dominate season 2 over?  After winning in Melbourne, the Ferrari number one has had difficulty with consistency over the last three rounds.  Having said that, he's only 10 points adrift from first place and a bounce back seems inevitable.<br /><br /><strong>One to watch:</strong><br />After a shakey start Eradicator is finally starting to show signs of the pace he showed in season 1 and 2. Some questioned his return but a strong 2nd place in Istabul silenced those critics.  With 3 wins from 42 races now getting to that top step hasn't been easy, however with confidence comes form and he could be the dark horse in Spain.<br /><br /><strong>Talking points:</strong><br /><strong>Overtaking:</strong><br />Overtaking is a rare sight at the Circuit de Catalunya and the dull races in recent years are exactly what this year's regulations are designed to prevent. The tyres will spice things up and the news that Pirelli is bringing a harder compound means the difference in grip between the prime and option tyres, a key factor for overtaking, will be even greater. The DRS is unlikely to be as effective as it has been in recent races as the corner at the end of the activation zone - turn one - is the first part of a sweeping chicane rather than a heavy braking zone. <br /><br /><strong>Updates:</strong><br />The teams traditionally target large update packages for the Spanish Grand Prix and this year is no different. The engineers and drivers know every corner of the circuit inside out from the miles of testing they have completed there over the years and can therefore gauge the success of a new part pretty quickly. This year Lotus, Sauber, Williams and McLaren are just four of the teams that have talked up their Barcelona packages, while many others will also make changes to their cars in the pursuit of shaving off a bit more lap time. <br /><br /><strong>Fast facts:</strong><br />- This will be the 4th Spanish GP - Previous winners - S1 Kikz, S2 Lambo, S3 Ghost<br />- The race has only ever been won once from Pole.  S2 Lambo.<br />- Kikz won the opening S1 race from 5th on the grid.<br />- Qualifying Record: Flouncy 1:22.397, which is likely to be smashed this weekend.<br /><br /><strong>Real life Trivia:</strong><br />- The Circuit de Catalunya was first used in F1 in 1991, a race remembered for Nigel Mansell's bold overtaking manoeuvre into turn one on Ayrton Senna.<br />- Barcelona hosted the Spanish Grand Prix four times between 1969 and 1975 in Montjuich Park. It was a tight and dangerous track that was eventually dropped in 1975 when five spectators were killed after Rolf Stommelen crashed over the barriers<br />- The park was later extensively re-developed for the 1992 Olympic Games<br />- Fernando Alonso is Spain's only Formula One race winner<br />- The very first race to run under the title of the "Spanish Grand Prix" was held in 1913, although it was actually run to touring car regulations rather than the grand prix formula of the day <br /><br /><strong>Circuit</strong><br />There is a very good reason why the cars return to the Circuit de Catalunya year-after-year to test. Its sweeping corners are very dependent on downforce, while the long straight requires a low level of drag. Put simply, if you're quick here you can be quick almost anywhere. Unfortunately all those fast corners come at the cost of reducing the chances of overtaking. Turn one remains a favourite place to try a move, while the big stop into turn 10 can be a possibility if the leading car makes a mistake through the tricky turn nine. The cars are at full throttle for 60% of the lap, meaning it is not the hardest track on engines. Pirelli is bringing its hard and soft compounds this weekend to combat front-left tyre graining, which will likely result in three stop strategies if it is a dry race. <br /><br /><strong>Betting</strong><br />Bobaj0r is the clear favourite at 4/6 odds, but anybody looking for a decent return on their money will be more insterested in Lambo or Flouncy at 11/2 and 9/2.  Ghost is now starting to show longer odds at 18/1.  The dark hourse however is Eradicator who's strong result in Istanbul has shorten his odds to 12/1<br /><br /><strong>Leggard prediction:</strong><br />In his current form you can't put a wheel past bobaj0r to make it 3 wins from 5 races.  However with unpredictable weather you never know.   </p>]]></content>
