              <thumbnail>1717</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[The entertaining Spanish Grand Prix has shown that the 2011 rules are a recipe for exciting racing on any circuit on the calendar. The one unknown that remains appears to be the crown jewel event that is the Monaco Grand Prix.  ]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>The entertaining Spanish Grand Prix has shown that the 2011 rules are a recipe for exciting racing on any circuit on the calendar. The one unknown that remains appears to be the crown jewel event that is the Monaco Grand Prix. Overtaking is not going to be easy by any stretch, but the tyre degradation and undercut available to earlier stoppers mean we should see positions changing and another intriguing race unfolding around the streets of the principality.<br /><br />The drivers are all still chasing one man: bobaj0r. While the close race in Barcelona will have heightened hopes of another McLaren challenge, Ferrari and Renault will want to spoil the McLaren drivers party as he goes for a 3rd consecutive race win.<br /><br /><strong>In Form:</strong><br />bobaj0r's form doesn't look like dipping any time soon, and while in certain parts of Spain Lambo and Flouncy matched him for pace he was close to untouchable. A clean getaway and error free race he will be the one to beat going into Monaco.<br /><br /><strong>Out of Form:</strong><br />It's no doubt that last seasons early title favourite Ghost is looking like a driver that's run out of steam. He was the talk of the town this time in season 3 and looked to have it in the books, but since loosing the title at the penultimate race in Abu Dahbi some months ago the Lotus driver has not looked comfortable all season and has struggled with both qualifying and race pace that made him so dangerous last season.<br /><br /><strong>One to Watch:</strong><br />Love it or hate it Monaco is a special challenge that almost all drivers enjoy. It rewards the brave and punishes even the smallest mistake. Renaults Lambo especially likes the 3.3km circuit having record two victories from three starts with his worst being second in Season 2. Ferrari's Flouncy is no slouch around here either having taken the only other victory in Season 2. Both will be on the lookout to displace the dominate start of bobaj0r.<br /><br /><strong>Talking points:</strong><br />DRS - It's been a talking point at many races this year, but the drivers seemed pretty united on one front for Monaco: it's too dangerous and should be banned. The FIA doesn't agree, and Charlie Whiting has said that it would be wrong to outlaw an overtaking aid where it could be needed the most. There is talk that drivers may be prevented from using it in the tunnel, but anyone who misjudges a braking point having used it will be heading for the barriers, and probably for a moan at the governing body. <br /><br /><strong>Traffic:</strong><br />It's always been notoriously difficult to pass around Monaco, in qualifying drivers will struggle to find clear air for a lap around the tight circuit, and the upshot in the race could be a lot of squabbling back markers for the leaders to overtake.<br /><br /><strong>Saftey Car</strong><br />So far this season there has been no safety cars, however with the tight circuit and no run off area's it's highly likely we could see several.<br /><br /><strong>Fast facts:</strong><br />- This will be the 4th Monaco GP - Previous Winners - S1+S3 Lambo, S2 Flouncy<br />- Despite overtaking being difficult, the race has only been won once from pole - S3 Lambo<br /><br /><strong>Real life trivia:</strong><br />- Monaco is renowned for its safety car periods as almost any accident requires one. In 2010 alone there were four occasions that the safety car was called upon, and historically there is a 60% chance of a safety car period in each race.<br />- Olivier Panis secured his one and only grand prix victory in Monaco in 1996, and in doing so set the record for winning from the highest grid position having started the race 14th.<br />- Two drivers have ended up in the harbour as results of crashes at Monaco - Alberto Ascari in 1955 and Paul Hawkins in 1965.<br />- A loose manhole cover last year caused Rubens Barrichello to have a major crash on the climb up to Massanet, and saw the race continue under the safety car for a few laps while stewards decided if it was unsafe. In his anger Barrichello threw his steering wheel out of the car and it was runover by Karun Chandhok's HRT.<br /> <br /><strong>Circuit:</strong><br />Monaco is worlds apart from the last track in Barcelona, and is the circuit where driver performance has the greatest influence. The tight and twisting slow speed corners require good traction and mechanical grip, while the length of the circuit - just 2 miles - means there are few straights of any note, with 180mph the top speed reached exiting the tunnel. The slowest corner on the circuit is the Loews hairpin, which is taken at just 30mph, and the quickest is the first chicane section of the swimming pool at 130mph. Being a street circuit the track surface is not overly abrasive, but cars need to be able to ride the bumps and undulations well. Overtaking is possible on the run out of the tunnel down in to the turn 10 chicane. <br /><br /><strong>Betting:</strong><br />Bobaj0rs odds seem to get shorter by the day, and he's favourite once again at 3/1. Flouncy and Lambo are reasonably priced at 5/1, especially taking in to account Lambos win last season. TurrbalTerror is a good outside bet at 18/1.<br /><br /><strong>Leggard Prediction:</strong><br />Bobaj0r may have stood at the podium in Spain but it's well known that Monaco is the hunting ground of Renault's Lambo. 2 wins from 3 starts at this venue he's well equipped to put pressure on the current championship leader so Leggard keeps it fresh by backing the Renault driver to pick-up 25 points.</p>]]></content>
