              <metaDescription><![CDATA[Spring settings restrictions will be removed for the Valencia GP this weekend after an ECU update fixed controller issues.]]></metaDescription>
              <thumbnail>1666</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[Spring settings restrictions will be removed for the Valencia GP this weekend after an ECU update fixed controller issues.]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p><img src="/media/18935/spring.jpg" width="342" height="190" alt="spring.jpg" style="float: right;"/>Since the start of season 4 spring settings have had a mandated maximum of 8, even though it's possible to run them at 11.  While there had been no way to police this FIA mandated limit, a gentlemans agreement was in place.</p>
<p>With ECU updates on November 23rd that will address this problem, and others, the restriction is no longer required.  This means that there will no longer be any suspicion of a team gaining an unfair advantage by running undetecably illegable springs.  What is unclear is how these ECU changes will impact on overall spring dynamics and the hanlding of the cars at large.  It's not infeasible that car handling may change in such a way as to dramatically effect the status quo of the season 4 title race.</p>]]></content>
