              <teaser><![CDATA[F1 2011 ECU's were released with faulty spring software. Patch 2 released today supposedly fixed this.  Mclaren have tested the new patch 2 settings and have results.]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>F1 2011 was released with a 11/11 spring bug, as <a href="/{localLink:1662}" title="Setup Spotlight: Springs">documented in previously by Mclaren</a>.  This definitely showed a massive drop of in performance as springs got increasingly more soft.  Every 2 units of springs resulted in approximately 2 seconds off the lap time.  In reality, more grip, up to a limit, should be offered by softer springs. As a result atomicf1, mandated that springs no greater than 8 on either front or rear could be used. </p>
<p>Patch 2 of F1 2011 released today contained a fix for the 11/11 spring bug.</p>
<p>Mclaren have just completed a comprehensive test at <a href="/{localLink:1219}" title="Catalunya">Catalunya</a>, cataloging the various spring settings and their impact on lap time.  The car setup used is the <a href="/{localLink:1780}" title="Dry Qualifying">Dry Qualifying</a> setup for this circuit, with the only adjustments being made to spring settings.</p>
<p>The following settings were used.</p>
<ul>
<li>1/1</li>
<li>6/3</li>
<li>6/11</li>
<li>8/8</li>
<li>11/11</li>
</ul>
<p>Mclaren found no major diffences in lap times. Certainly not the differences that were found during their test earlier in the season.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>The fastest setup was 6/11 springs, which makes sense as softer front settings would decrease understeer, of which <a href="/{localLink:1266}" title="TurrbalTerror">TurrbalTerror</a>'s driving style produces in large quantities. </p>
<p> </p>
