              <metaDescription><![CDATA[Silverstone is the host for round 9 of the Atomic F1 championship as drivers and fans flock to the famous race track to see the cream of the crop of Atomic F1's elite take on the challenging circuit.]]></metaDescription>
              <thumbnail>1826</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[Silverstone is the host for round 9 of the Atomic F1 championship as drivers and fans flock to the famous race track to see the cream of the crop of Atomic F1's elite take on the challenging circuit.]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p><b><img src="/media/26738/uk-flag-6.jpg" width="380" height="257" alt="uk-flag-6.jpg" style="float: left;"/>Stiff upper lip</b><br />Silverstone is the host for round 9 of the Atomic F1 championship as drivers and fans flock to the famous race track to see the cream of the crop of Atomic F1's elite take on the challenging circuit. An all new pit and paddock complex will provide a new challenge as drivers customise to the new layout. Who will triumph at the famous circuit? Atomic F1 pundit Jonnathen Leggard peers inside the crystal ball and tries to dissect who will step atop the podium at the British Grand Prix.<br /><br /><b>On Form</b><br />In what's becoming an almost dull section of this feature, McLaren's Bobaj0r still stands as the one to beat. Since shrugging off the incident at Monaco he's won at both the Canadian and European GP's and will be looking to join a very special club of drivers who have one 3 consecutive races. Now with a more comfortable lead the McLaren driver won't be looking to slack off with plenty of races to come and the second place finish of Ghost in last seasons championship a stark reminder that you can never relax. <br /><br /><b>Out Of Form</b><br />ET Rom's explosive pace at the Melbourne GP was hope that the famous silver arrow would play a role in this seasons championship. However some disappointing results and an equal worst 7th place in Valencia has left some fans scratching their heads. On the flip side race pace has been solid and for all counts the Mercedes has been the 'best of the rest' for most of the season. However you can't help but feel ET is knocking on the door of another podium sooner rather than later.<br /><br /><b>One to Watch</b><br />Ferrari's Flouncy hasn't had the best of seasons so far. Bad luck and some slight off form pace has seen him drop to 3rd just a few points off the Renault of Lambo in the championship standings. However Silverstone is a favourite track and the Ferrari driver has traditionally been very fast around here in the past. Some say that he's the most likely to challenge the McLaren's for the win on Sunday. Definitely one to watch.<br /><br /><b>Talking Points</b><br />Pirelli dabbled with the idea of bringing the medium compound tyre to Silverstone but ultimately settled with the original plan of bringing hard and soft. The Italian firm knows that its rubber is in for a tough weekend as it is tortured through the high-speed sections, but is confident its product is up to the challenge. The bigger question is whether some of the teams are up to the demands of the hard compound tyre. The only time this specific compound has been used in race conditions was at the Spanish Grand Prix.<br /><br /><b>The Future of Silverstone</b><br />Silverstone hosted the first Formula One Grand Prix in 1950 and has built itself on the reputation of being "The Home of Motorsport" ever since. It's a circuit worthy of the title and now it has the facilities to match thanks to the recent opening of the Wing. The brand new pit and paddock complex looks as though it will be on par with far-flung venues such as Shanghai and Korea, which is crucial with F1 searching for more and more cash-rich venues to hold races. There will undoubtedly be a few teething issues with the new facilities, but the sheer good will built up since the first impromptu race on the site in 1947 means there should be very few complaints. <br /><br /><b>Fast Facts</b><br />- This will be the 4th British Grand Prix, previous winners - S1 Ghost, S2 Flouncy, S3, GHost<br />- Qualifying Record - 1:31.085 Ghost - S3<br />- The race has never been won from pole position.<br /><br /><b>Real Fast Facts</b><br />- Keke Rosberg averaged 160.938mph in a Williams when he set pole position at the 1985 British GP, making Silverstone the world's fastest GP circuit at the time.<br />- British drivers have won their home grand prix 21 times, more than any other nation.<br />- The Maggots, Becketts, Chapel complex is one of the fastest corner sequences on the calendar and is entered at 185 mph, with drivers pulling 5G through Becketts.<br />- Jim Clark led John Surtees and Graham Hill in an all-British one-two-three at Silverstone in 1963.<br /><br /><b>Trivia</b><br />- The name Silverstone derives from the Old English for "wooded area".<br />- In the early years of the event spectators were not allowed in the circuit's infield area for fear they might damage the local farmer's crops.<br />- The circuit has seen many changes down the years. The last major alteration before last year's was in 1990 when Becketts was revised, a new section between Stowe and Club was added and a five-corner complex before Woodcote was built.<br />- Silverstone hosted the inaugural round of the Formula One world championship on May 13 1950. Giuseppe Farina won in an Alfa Romeo 158, with an average speed of 90.95mph<br /><br /><b>Circuit</b><br />Silverstone has long been a favourite among the drivers and the alterations to the circuit last year didn't change that. The high-speed corners were retained and even added to with the new nearly-flat-out Abbey Corner that features a sizable bump on entry. The extra 0.8 kilometres of track, added roughly 10 seconds in lap time but opened up some good viewing opportunities for spectators and a couple of overtaking opportunities at Village and Brooklands. This year Brooklands should see even more passing as it marks the end of the DRS zone down the long Wellington Straight. <br /><br /><b>Betting</b><br />There's no getting away from Bobaj0r's dominance so far this season which in many respects is paralleling Sebastian Vettels same season. The McLaren driver starts at 8/11, but the surprise number two is Ferrari's Flouncy at 6/1 followed by Renault's Lambo of 8/1. TurrbalTerror's solid second at Valencia sees his odds strengthen to 9/1. Two time winner Ghost based on previous results is a fair bet at 12/1 as long as he tries to qualify.<br /><br /><b>Leggard Prediction</b><br />Race favourite Bobaj0r will most likely join the select club of Flouncy and Ghost to have won 3 consecutive races.</p>]]></content>
