              <thumbnail>1839</thumbnail>
              <teaser><![CDATA[Silverstone marked a turning point in the Atomic F1 Season but it's unlikely it will tip the balance in this year's championship. McLaren's bobaj0r just has to hold everything together for the next 9 races to secure his first world championship. ]]></teaser>
              <content><![CDATA[<p>Silverstone marked a turning point in the Atomic F1 Season but it's unlikely it will tip the balance in this year's championship. McLaren's bobaj0r just has to hold everything together for the next 9 races to secure his first world championship. However any notion that the rest of the season will be dull affair couldn't be further from the truth. So we once again shake the magic eight ball and put our cards on the table. Who will master the German Grand Prix? <br /><br /><b>On Form:</b><br />While it would be right to once again mention McLaren's bobaj0r here, recently his team mate TurrbalTerror, has shown strong pace, and is knocking on the door for a victory. Showed strong pace in Silverstone and Valencia and the Nurburgring should play to his strengths and driving style. Has shown good qualifying pace, and a win just seems around the corner. It would seem that the only thing that could hold him back is from the other side of the garage. With the championship poised and the team wanting to ensure they secure the drivers championship, could we see team tactics play a part?<br /><br /><br /><b>Out Of Form:</b><br />Ferrari has been disappointingly quiet this few races. Some insiders say that they are already conceding the season to focus on pet races and next years car. Flouncy finished a very quiet 4th while his team mate BreakerMorant crossed the line 9th. But while the 50 point gap seems insurmountable, it only takes one or two good results, and some bad luck up the top and this could be a very different story. One team to watch.<br /><br /><b>One To Watch:</b><br />Williams continued there form resurgence with a well deserved podium at Silverstone. The Williams has looked strong in race trim for some time and the steady improvement has yielded two podiums this season so far. Exciting prospect for next season and could be in high demand when teams start finalising their driver line ups for season 5.<br /><br /><b>Talking Points:</b><br />The Championship:<br />We keep hearing that the championship is not over, but bobaj0r's current form and some basic maths appear to tell a different story. It's true that Renault is more competitive now than it has been at any other point this season, but bobaj0r needs some serious bad luck not to take this seasons world champion by this year's Brazilian Grand Prix. However, stranger things have happened in F1 and as proved in season 3, until it's mathematically impossible there is always a chance.<br /><br /><br /><b>Fast Facts:</b><br />This will be the 4th German Grand Prix, but the first at the Nurburgring. Past Winners - S1 Lambo, S2 HolyGhost, S3 HolyGhost.<br /><br /><b>Real Life Facts:</b></p>
<ul>
<li>The original Nurburgring was built to help solve unemployment issues in the Eifel region following World War One. A workforce of approximately 25,000 constructed the 14.2 mile circuit at a cost of 14.1 million Reichsmarks.</li>
<li>The old circuit is now a toll road open to the public with a lap costing €24 a pop.</li>
<li>The first F1 race on the new circuit was held in 1984 and won by Alain Prost, but he was beaten by Ayrton Senna earlier that year in a race that pitted F1 drivers old and new against each other in identical Mercedes 190Es.</li>
<li>The circuit currently alternates with Hockenheim as the venue of the German Grand Prix.</li>
<li>The first German Grand Prix was held in 1926 at the Avus circuit in central Berlin.</li>
<li>Ferrari holds the record number of wins by a constructor at the German Grand Prix, with a total of 20. It is also the highest number of wins by a constructor at any grand prix.</li>
<li>An F1 car is on full throttle for 63% of an average lap at the Nurburgring.</li>
<li>Cars tend to make 67 gear changes per lap at the Nurburgring.</li>
</ul>
<p><br /><b>Circuit:</b><br />Although the modern circuit pales in comparison to the original, the Nurburgring is still a decent race track in its own right. Modifications to the opening part of the lap in 2002 created an obvious overtaking opportunity and more exciting starts, and with the DRS zone on the long back straight into the NGK chicane - another passing spot - there should be plenty of action this weekend. The high-speed sector two requires a good balance but traction and stability under braking are also rewarded in sectors one and three. <br /><br /><b>Betting:</b><br />Bobaj0r is favourite to win in at even odds, ahead of Lambo at 4/1. TurrbalTerror is worth an each way bet at 5/1 and Williams Eradicator84 and Ferrari's Flouncy share 10/1 odds.<br /><br /><b>Leggard Prediction:</b><br />Looked strong before running out of fuel, and the inside scoop is that every setup and practice work has been going on the last few days in the McLaren garage. TurrbalTerror to take his first race win with second bobaj0r followed by Atomic Lambo to round out the podium.</p>]]></content>
